    slug: "maqamat-e-samood",
    description: `Maqamat e Samood is an informative and visually rich Urdu-language Islamic book that investigates the historical locations, archaeological evidence, and material remains associated with the ancient civilisation of Thamud, the people mentioned in the Quran who were destroyed for their rejection of Prophet Salih (peace be upon him) and their arrogant defiance of Allah's signs. The book provides a thorough examination of the Thamudic civilization by combining Quranic narration, classical Islamic historical sources, and modern archaeological research to present a comprehensive picture of this remarkable people and their eventual downfall. The author begins with a detailed analysis of the Quranic verses that mention the Thamud, presenting the complete narrative of their story as told across multiple surahs of the Quran. This includes the description of their advanced civilisation, their skill in carving magnificent dwellings out of mountains, their material prosperity, their idolatrous practices, the mission of Prophet Salih, the extraordinary miracle of the she-camel, their killing of the she-camel, and the devastating punishment that Allah sent upon them. The book then turns to the geographical and archaeological dimension, exploring the regions of north-western Arabia, particularly the area around Madain Salih (also known as Al-Hijr or Hegra), where the most significant Thamudic archaeological remains are found. The author discusses the rock-hewn tombs, the inscriptions in the Thamudic script, the artistic reliefs, and other archaeological features that have been discovered and studied by modern researchers, providing detailed descriptions and photographic documentation of these remarkable sites. The book examines what these material remains reveal about the Thamudic civilisation, including their social organisation, religious practices, artistic achievements, and daily life, drawing connections between the archaeological evidence and the Quranic description of the Thamud. The author also addresses the various opinions of classical and contemporary scholars regarding the identification of Thamudic sites, the timeline of their civilisation, and the relationship between the Thamud and other ancient Arabian civilisations. Throughout the book, the discussion of historical and archaeological material is consistently linked to the spiritual and moral lessons that the Quran derives from the story of the Thamud, ensuring that the reader appreciates both the fascinating historical content and its profound religious significance. The book serves as a reminder of the consequences of rejecting divine guidance and the impermanence of even the most advanced and powerful civilisations. Written in scholarly yet accessible Urdu, Maqamat e Samood is recommended for students of Quranic studies, enthusiasts of Islamic history and archaeology, and any reader interested in the remarkable stories of ancient civilisations preserved in divine scripture.`,
